Wait — the route file uses `db.query` for both reads AND writes. Let me check... yes, the UPDATE is using `db.query` (which goes to the read replica), not `db.write`. But it works sometimes because... hmm, that shouldn't work at all actually. Let me double check.

Actually, looking more carefully, the UPDATE does go through `db.query` which hits the read replica. But PostgreSQL read replicas don't accept writes — so the UPDATE should fail entirely. But users ARE getting updated (sometimes). What's going on?

OK actually I just realized our infrastructure team recently set up pgbouncer in front of both pools and it might be routing some queries to the primary. Regardless, the stale reads are the symptom we need to fix.

